#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "OpenSSH key management, Part 1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:13
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this series, you'll learn how RSA and DSA authentication work, and see how\n"
"to set up passwordless authentication the right way. In the first article of\n"
"the series, Daniel Robbins focuses on introducing the RSA and DSA\n"
"authentication protocols and showing you how to get them working over the\n"
"network.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding RSA/DSA authentication"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:34
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Many of us use the excellent OpenSSH (see <uri\n"
"link=\"#resources\">Resources</uri> later in this article) as a secure, encrypted\n"
"replacement for the venerable <c>telnet</c> and <c>rsh</c> commands. One of\n"
"OpenSSH's more intriguing features is its ability to authenticate users using\n"
"the RSA and DSA authentication protocols, which are based on a pair of\n"
"complementary numerical keys. As one of its main appeals, RSA and DSA\n"
"authentication promise the capability of establishing connections to remote\n"
"systems <e>without supplying a password</e>. While this is appealing, new\n"
"OpenSSH users often configure RSA/DSA the quick and dirty way, resulting in\n"
"passwordless logins, but opening up a big security hole in the process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is RSA/DSA authentication?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:53
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"SSH, specifically OpenSSH (a completely free implementation of SSH), is an\n"
"incredible tool. Like <c>telnet</c> or <c>rsh</c>, the ssh client can be used\n"
"to log in to a remote machine. All that's required is for this remote machine\n"
"to be running <c>sshd</c>, the <c>ssh</c> server process. However, unlike\n"
"<c>telnet</c>, the ssh protocol is very secure. It uses special algorithms to\n"
"encrypt the data stream, ensure data stream integrity and even perform\n"
"authentication in a safe and secure way.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, while <c>ssh</c> is really great, there is a certain component of\n"
"<c>ssh</c> functionality that is often ignored, dangerously misused, or simply\n"
"misunderstood. This component is OpenSSH's RSA/DSA key authentication system,\n"
"an alternative to the standard secure password authentication system that\n"
"OpenSSH uses by default.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:71
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"OpenSSH's RSA and DSA authentication protocols are based on a pair of specially\n"
"generated cryptographic keys, called the <e>private key</e> and the <e>public\n"
"key</e>. The advantage of using these key-based authentication systems is that\n"
"in many cases, it's possible to establish secure connections without having to\n"
"manually type in a password.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:79
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"While the key-based authentication protocols are relatively secure, problems\n"
"arise when users take certain shortcuts in the name of convenience, without\n"
"fully understanding their security implications. In this article, we'll take a\n"
"good look at how to correctly use RSA and DSA authentication protocols without\n"
"exposing ourselves to any unnecessary security risks. In my next article, I'll\n"
"show you how to use <c>ssh-agent</c> to cache decrypted private keys, and \n"
"introduce <c>keychain</c>, an <c>ssh-agent</c> front-end that offers a number \n"
"of convenience advantages without sacrificing security. If you've always wanted \n"
"to get the hang of the more advanced authentication features of OpenSSH, then \n"
"read on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "How RSA/DSA keys work"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:98
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here's a quick general overview of how RSA/DSA keys work. Let's start with a \n"
"hypothetical scenario where we'd like to use RSA authentication to allow a \n"
"local Linux workstation (named <e>localbox</e>) to open a remote shell on \n"
"<e>remotebox</e>, a machine at our ISP. Right now, when we try to connect to \n"
"<e>remotebox</e> using the <c>ssh</c> client, we get the following prompt:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "Connecting to remotebox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:106
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ssh drobbins@remotebox</i>\n"
"drobbins@remotebox's password:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here we see an example of the <c>ssh</c> <e>default</e> way of handling\n"
"authentication. Namely, it asks for the password of the <e>drobbins</e> account\n"
"on <e>remotebox</e>. If we type in our password for <e>remotebox</e>,\n"
"<c>ssh</c> uses its secure password authentication protocol, transmitting our\n"
"password over to <e>remotebox</e> for verification. However, unlike what\n"
"<c>telnet</c> does, here our password is encrypted so that it can not be\n"
"intercepted by anyone sniffing our data connection. Once <e>remotebox</e>\n"
"authenticates our supplied password against its password database, if\n"
"successful, we're allowed to log on and are greeted with a <e>remotebox</e>\n"
"shell prompt. While the <c>ssh</c> default authentication method is quite\n"
"secure, RSA and DSA authentication open up some new possibilities.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:125
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, unlike the <c>ssh</c> secure password authentication, RSA\n"
"authentication requires some initial configuration. We need to perform these\n"
"initial configuration steps only once. After that, RSA authentication between\n"
"<e>localbox</e> and <e>remotebox</e> will be totally painless. To set up RSA\n"
"authentication, we first need to generate a pair of keys, one private and one\n"
"public. These two keys have some very interesting properties. The public key\n"
"can be used to encrypt a message, and only the holder of the private key can\n"
"decrypt it. The public key can only be used for <e>encryption</e>, and the\n"
"private key can only be used for <e>decryption</e> of a message encoded by the\n"
"matching public key. The RSA (and DSA) authentication protocols use the special\n"
"properties of key pairs to perform secure authentication, without needing to\n"
"transmit any confidential information over the network.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:140
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To get RSA or DSA authentication working, we perform a single one-time\n"
"configuration step. We copy our <e>public key</e> over to <e>remotebox</e>.\n"
"The public key is called \"public\" for a reason. Since it can only be used to\n"
"<e>encrypt</e> messages for us, we don't need to be too concerned about it\n"
"falling into the wrong hands. Once our public key has been copied over to\n"
"<e>remotebox</e> and placed in a special file\n"
"(<path>~/.ssh/authorized_keys</path>) so that <e>remotebox</e>'s <c>sshd</c>\n"
"can locate it, we're ready to use RSA authentication to log onto\n"
"<e>remotebox</e>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:152
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To do this, we simply type <c>ssh drobbins@remotebox</c> at <e>localbox</e>'s\n"
"console, as we always have. However, this time, <c>ssh</c> lets\n"
"<e>remotebox</e>'s <c>sshd</c> know that it would like to use the RSA\n"
"authentication protocol. What happens next is rather interesting.\n"
"<e>Remotebox</e>'s <c>sshd</c> generates a random number, and encrypts it using\n"
"our public key that we copied over earlier. Then, it sends this encrypted\n"
"random number back to the <c>ssh</c> running on <e>localbox</e>. In turn, our\n"
"<c>ssh</c> uses our <e>private key</e> to decrypt this random number, and then\n"
"sends it back to <e>remotebox</e>, saying in effect \"See, I really <e>do</e>\n"
"hold the matching private key; I was able to successfully decrypt your\n"
"message!\" Finally, <c>sshd</c> concludes that we should be allowed to log in,\n"
"since we hold a matching private key. Thus, the fact that we hold a matching\n"
"private key grants us access to <e>remotebox</e>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:170
#, no-wrap
msgid "Two observations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:174
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are two important observations about the RSA and DSA authentication. The\n"
"first is that we really only need to generate one pair of keys. We can then\n"
"copy our public key to the remote machines that we'd like to access and they\n"
"will all happily authenticate against our single private key. In other words,\n"
"we don't need a key pair for <e>every</e> system we'd like to access. Just one\n"
"pair will suffice.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:183
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The other observation is that our <e>private key should not fall into the wrong\n"
"hands</e>. The private key is the one thing that grants us access to our remote\n"
"systems, and anyone that possesses our private key is granted exactly the same\n"
"privileges that we are. Just as we wouldn't want strangers to have keys to our\n"
"house, we should protect our private key from unauthorized use. In the world of\n"
"bits and bytes, this means that no one should be able to read or copy our\n"
"private key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:193
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Of course, the <c>ssh</c> developers are aware of the private keys' importance,\n"
"and have built a few safeguards into <c>ssh</c> and <c>ssh-keygen</c> so that\n"
"our private key is not abused. First, <c>ssh</c> is configured to print out a\n"
"big warning message if our key has file permissions that would allow it to be\n"
"read by anyone but us. Secondly, when we create our public/private key pair\n"
"using <c>ssh-keygen</c>, <c>ssh-keygen</c> will ask us to enter a passphrase.\n"
"If we do, our private key will be encrypted using this passphrase, so that even\n"
"if it is stolen, it will be useless to anyone who doesn't happen to know the\n"
"passphrase. Armed with that knowledge, let's take a look at how to configure\n"
"<c>ssh</c> to use the RSA and DSA authentication protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:208
#, no-wrap
msgid "ssh-keygen up close"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The first step in setting up RSA authentication begins with generating a\n"
"public/private key pair. RSA authentication is the original form of <c>ssh</c>\n"
"key authentication, so RSA should work with any version of OpenSSH, although I\n"
"recommend that you install the most recent version available, which was\n"
"openssh-2.9_p2 at the time this article was written. Generate a pair of RSA\n"
"keys as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:220
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using ssh-keygen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ssh-keygen</i>\n"
"Generating public/private rsa1 key pair.\n"
"Enter file in which to save the key (/home/drobbins/.ssh/identity): <comment>(hit enter)</comment>\n"
"Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase): <comment>(enter a passphrase)</comment>\n"
"Enter same passphrase again: <comment>(enter it again)</comment>\n"
"Your identification has been saved in /home/drobbins/.ssh/identity.\n"
"Your public key has been saved in /home/drobbins/.ssh/identity.pub.\n"
"The key fingerprint is:\n"
"a4:e7:f2:39:a7:eb:fd:f8:39:f1:f1:7b:fe:48:a1:09 drobbins@localbox\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:233
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When <c>ssh-keygen</c> asks for a default location for the key, we hit enter \n"
"to accept the default of <path>/home/drobbins/.ssh/identity</path>.\n"
"<c>ssh-keygen</c> will store the private key at the above path, and the\n"
"<e>public</e> key will be stored right next to it, in a file called \n"
"identity.pub.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:241
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Also note that <c>ssh-keygen</c> prompted us to enter a passphrase. When\n"
"prompted, we entered a good passphrase (seven or more hard-to-predict\n"
"characters). <c>ssh-keygen</c> then encrypted our private key\n"
"(<path>~/.ssh/identity</path>) using this passphrase so that our private key\n"
"will be useless to anyone who does not know it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:251
#, no-wrap
msgid "The quick compromise"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:255
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When we specify a passphrase, it allows <c>ssh-keygen</c> to secure our private\n"
"key against misuse, but it also creates a minor inconvenience. Now, every time\n"
"we try to connect to our <e>drobbins@remotebox</e> account using <c>ssh</c>,\n"
"<c>ssh</c> will prompt us to enter the passphrase so that it can decrypt our\n"
"private key and use it for RSA authentication. Again, we won't be typing in our\n"
"password for the <e>drobbins</e> account on <e>remotebox</e>, we'll be typing\n"
"in the passphrase needed to locally decrypt our private key.  Once our private\n"
"key is decrypted, our <c>ssh</c> client will take care of the rest. While the\n"
"mechanics of using our remote password and the RSA passphrase are completely\n"
"different, in practice we're still prompted to type a \"secret phrase\" into\n"
"<c>ssh</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:268
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:285
#, no-wrap
msgid "Logging in with passphrase"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:269
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ssh drobbins@remotebox</i>\n"
"Enter passphrase for key '/home/drobbins/.ssh/identity': <comment>(enter passphrase)</comment>\n"
"Last login: Thu Jun 28 20:28:47 2001 from localbox.gentoo.org \n"
"\n"
"Welcome to remotebox!\n"
"\n"
"$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:279
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here's where people are often mislead into a quick compromise. A lot of the\n"
"time, people will create unencrypted private keys just so that they don't need\n"
"to type in a password. That way, they simply type in the ssh command, and\n"
"they're immediately authenticated via RSA (or DSA) and logged in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:286
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ssh drobbins@remotebox</i>\n"
"Last login: Thu Jun 28 20:28:47 2001 from localbox.gentoo.org \n"
"\n"
"Welcome to remotebox!\n"
"\n"
"$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:295
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, while this is convenient, you shouldn't use this approach without\n"
"fully understanding its security impact. With an unencrypted private key, if\n"
"anyone ever hacks into <e>localbox</e>, they'll also get automatic access to\n"
"<e>remotebox</e> and any other systems that have been configured with the\n"
"public key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:303
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"I know what you're thinking. Passwordless authentication, despite being a bit\n"
"risky does seem really appealing. I totally agree. But <e>there is a better\n"
"way!</e> Stick with me, and I'll show you how to gain the benefits of\n"
"passwordless authentication without compromising your private key security.\n"
"I'll show you how to masterfully use <c>ssh-agent</c> (the thing that makes\n"
"<e>secure</e> passwordless authentication possible in the first place) in my\n"
"next article. Now, let's get ready to use <c>ssh-agent</c> by setting up RSA\n"
"and DSA authentication. Here step-by-step directions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:316
#, no-wrap
msgid "RSA key pair generation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:320
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To set up RSA authentication, we'll need to perform the one-time step of\n"
"generating a public/private key pair. We do this by typing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:324
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generating keys..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:325
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>ssh-keygen</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:329
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Accept the default key location when prompted (typically\n"
"<path>~/.ssh/identity</path> and <path>~/.ssh/identity.pub</path> for the\n"
"public key), and provide <c>ssh-keygen</c> with a secure passphrase. Once\n"
"<c>ssh-keygen</c> completes, you'll have a public key as well as a\n"
"passphrase-encrypted private key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:339
#, no-wrap
msgid "RSA public key install"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:343
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next, we'll need to configure remote systems running <c>sshd</c> to use our\n"
"<e>public</e> RSA key for authentication. Typically, this is done by copying\n"
"the public key to the remote system as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:348
#, no-wrap
msgid "Copying the public key"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:349
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>scp ~/.ssh/identity.pub drobbins@remotebox:</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:353
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Since RSA authentication isn't fully set up yet, we'll be prompted to enter our\n"
"password on <e>remotebox</e>. Do so. Then, log in to <e>remotebox</e> and\n"
"append the public key to the <path>~/.ssh/authorized_keys</path> file like so:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:358
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing the public key"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:359
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ssh drobbins@remotebox</i>\n"
"drobbins@remotebox's password: <comment>(enter password)</comment>\n"
"Last login: Thu Jun 28 20:28:47 2001 from localbox.gentoo.org \n"
"\n"
"Welcome to remotebox!\n"
"\n"
"$ <i>cat identity.pub >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys</i>\n"
"$ <i>exit</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:370
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, with RSA authentication configured, we should be prompted to enter our RSA\n"
"<e>passphrase</e> (rather than our <e>password</e>) when we try to connect to \n"
"<e>remotebox</e> using <c>ssh</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:375
#, no-wrap
msgid "Logging in with pubkey authentication"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:376
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ssh drobbins@remotebox</i>\n"
"Enter passphrase for key '/home/drobbins/.ssh/identity': \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:381
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Hurray, RSA authentication configuration complete! If you weren't prompted for\n"
"a passphrase, here are a few things to try. First, try logging in by typing\n"
"<c>ssh -1 drobbins@remotebox</c>. This will tell ssh to only use version 1 of\n"
"the ssh protocol, and may be required if for some reason the remote system is\n"
"defaulting to DSA authentication. If that doesn't work, make sure that you\n"
"don't have a line that reads <c>RSAAuthentication no</c> in your\n"
"<path>/etc/ssh/ssh_config</path>. If you do, comment it out by pre-pending it\n"
"with a \"#\". Otherwise, try contacting the <e>remotebox</e> system administrator\n"
"and verifying that they have enabled RSA authentication on their end and have\n"
"the appropriate settings in <path>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:396
#, no-wrap
msgid "DSA key generation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:400
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"While RSA keys are used by version 1 of the <c>ssh</c> protocol, DSA keys are\n"
"used for protocol level 2, an updated version of the <c>ssh</c> protocol. Any\n"
"modern version of OpenSSH should be able to use both RSA and DSA keys.\n"
"Generating DSA keys using OpenSSH's <c>ssh-keygen</c> can be done similarly to\n"
"RSA in the following manner:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:407
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generating a DSA key pair"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:408
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>ssh-keygen -t dsa</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:412
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Again, we'll be prompted for a passphrase. Enter a secure one. We'll also be\n"
"prompted for a location to save our DSA keys. The default, normally\n"
"<path>~/.ssh/id_dsa</path> and <path>~/.ssh/id_dsa.pub</path>, should be fine.\n"
"After our one-time DSA key generation is complete, it's time to install our DSA\n"
"public key to remote systems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:422
#, no-wrap
msgid "DSA public key install"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:426
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Again, DSA public key installation is almost identical to RSA. For DSA, we'll\n"
"want to copy our <path>~/.ssh/id_dsa.pub</path> file to <e>remotebox</e>, and\n"
"then append it to the <path>~/.ssh/authorized_keys2</path> on <e>remotebox</e>.\n"
"Note that this file has a different name than the RSA\n"
"<path>authorized_keys</path> file. Once configured, we should be able to log in\n"
"to <e>remotebox</e> by typing in our DSA private key passphrase rather than\n"
"typing in our actual <e>remotebox</e> password.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:436
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Nowadays you should only use version 2 of the ssh protocol, as version 1 has\n"
"weaknesses.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:443
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next time"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/openssh-key-management-p1.xml:447
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Right now, you should have RSA or DSA authentication working, but you still\n"
"need to type in your passphrase for every new connection. In my next article,\n"
"we'll see how to use <c>ssh-agent</c>, a really nice system that allows us to\n"
"establish connections <e>without</e> supplying a password, but also allows us\n"
"to keep our private keys encrypted on disk. I'll also introduce\n"
"<c>keychain</c>, a very handy <c>ssh-agent</c> front-end that makes\n"
"<c>ssh-agent</c> even more secure, convenient, and fun to use. Until then,\n"
"check out the handy resources below to keep yourself on track.\n"
msgstr ""

